Q. Which of the following statements are true for an Amazon CloudWatch alarm? (Select THREE.)

- An alarm can be created by using only the CloudWatch console.
- The number of evaluation periods for an alarm, multiplied by the length of each evaluation period, cannot exceed 1 day.
- You can create an alarm that watches multiple metrics.
- An alarm can be in one of three states: OK, ALARM, or INSUFFICIENT_DATA.
- You cannot change the name of an existing alarm.CloudWatch preserves alarm history for a month.


A SysOps administrator has set up an Amazon CloudWatch alarm to provide an alert when a specific Amazon EC2 instance's CPU utilization is more than 60%. The CloudWatch alarm is configured as follows:

Datapoints to Alarm: 3
Period: 5 minutes
Evaluation Periods: 3
Evaluation Range: 5
Treatment of missing data points: not breaching
The CPU utilization of the EC2 instance is sustained above 65% in the time frame between 07:00 and 14:00. The SysOps administrator stops the EC2 instance at 07:09 and restarts the EC2 instance at 07:16. The EC2 instance resumes its CPU utilization of more than 65%.

At 07:40, what is the status of the alarm?















































